fields.name: Epidemic definiton(text)
fields.source: The term epidemic describes those diseases caused by infectious microorganisms that occasionally occur in large numbers. Once introduced into a population,infectious microorganisms such as viruses and bacteria can spread from person to person. And so long as each person transmits the infection to more than other person, the number of cases of disease will grow and grow exponentially.  It is not the disease that is spreading. But rather, the organisms that cause the disease. The term is here to stay, of course. And it's a good reminder that there are diseases whose underlying cause cannot spread from person to person. For example, diseases that have genetic causes, or diseases that are due to toxins in the environment. Disease when caused by microorganisms is always an outcome of an intricate interplay between the biology of the microorganism, the biology of the host, and the environment.   For example, Matt and I could be exposed to the exact same virus, yet one of us might develop a disease with all its symptoms while the other one will stay perfectly healthy.

fields.name: Reproductive number (text)
fields.source: The question of how epidemics start is a complicated one. However, we can certainly propose a basic condition for an epidemic, which is that the first person who is infected with the pathogen must, on average, pass that infection on to at least one other person. If that fails to happen, the pathogen will fail to spread. If more than one person gets infected, and they subsequently infect more than one person, then the number of affected individuals will increase exponentially and we would have an epidemic.  This idea is described in epidemiology by the basic reproductive number R0. The formal definition for R0 is the average number of secondary infections, generated by the first infectious individual in a population of completely susceptible individuals. So, at the start of an epidemic, the first infected individual, infects R0 more individuals, who in turn infect R0 more and so on until something slows this process down.  Now let's consider the start of an epidemic and what properties might contribute to the rate of epidemic spread. Certainly, the longer an individual remains infectious, the longer they can transmit to others. So, we would expect R0 to increase with the length of infection. Let's call it L.  The more susceptible hosts there are to infect, let's call that number S, the greater the potential there is for the first individual to transmit their infection. These two terms together give us the potential number of contacts over the course of an infection.  Now, conditional on the number of potential contacts, R0 will also depend on how transmissible a pathogen is. So now, overall, we can characterize R0 as the product of the number of susceptible hosts S, the length of time an individual is infectious L, and the transmissibility beta. And from the basic conditions stated earlier, an outbreak is only likely to spread if R0 is greater than 1. It is also worth noting that R0 is a measure of the average or expected outcome of transmission.
